<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-estimations-and-approximations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Estimations and Approximations</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.1 Approximation and Errors
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine errors from measurements of quantities
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan" xml:id="lesson-plan-measurement">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery: Measurement Accuracy</title>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    40 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Students will understand that using different measuring tools leads to variations in accuracy, consistency, and human error when measuring the same object.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize students into small groups and provide them with 15 cm rulers, 30 cm rulers, and metre rules. Guide the groups during the reflection phase to help them connect multiple placements of a shorter tool with the accumulation of human error.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Work in <term>Groups</term> to do the following measurement activity.
            </p>
           
            <p>
                Measure the length of the Locker using each of the following tools and record your measurements in the table below.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>15</m> cm ruler.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>30</m> cm ruler.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Metre rule.</p>
                    </li>
                    
                </ol>
            </p>
            <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Measuring Tool</cell>
                    <cell>Length (cm)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>15</m> cm</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>30</m> cm</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Metre Rule</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                <term>Part B: Comparing Results</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare the measurements obtained using the different tools. What do you notice?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Why might different tools produce slightly different estimates of the same length?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Which measurement tool do you think gives the best estimate of the Locker length? Explain your answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What can you conclude about approximation when measuring lengths?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Part C: Investigating Differences</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare your results with another group's measurements.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss how human error may have affected the results.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Guided Reflection:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What happens if the ruler is not placed exactly at the edge of the desk?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Does the thickness of the measuring tool affect accuracy?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Can two correct measurements still be slightly different? Explain.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                What are the ways of improving accuracy when measuring long objects?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan" xml:id="lesson-plan-structured-instruction">
    <title>Structured Instruction: Formalizing Measurement Concepts</title>
    <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    20 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts of precision, consistency, and sources of experimental error discovered during the practical activity.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
        <ol marker="(i)">
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Use the students' filled tables to point out variations in the results. Highlight that the <m>15</m> cm ruler required multiple placements, which introduced a new chance for error each time the ruler was moved.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Defining Accuracy and Consistency:</alert> Explain that the metre rule gives the most consistent result because it measures the desk in a single step, minimizing alignment errors.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Human Error Mitigation:</alert> Formalize methods for improving accuracy, such as aligning the zero-mark of the tool exactly with the edge, keeping the tool flat, and reading the scale directly from above to avoid parallax error.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </paragraphs>
</axiom>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>

        <p>
            Measurement is never perfectly exact. Every measurement has a small error due to limitations of measuring instruments and human errors.
        </p>
        <p>
            Differences in results may arise due to:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Different measuring instruments (resolution and size)</p> 
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Parallax error (incorrect viewing angle)</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Starting point misalignment</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Human estimation differences</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            Because of these limitations, we often give measurements as approximations rather than exact values.
        </p>

        <p>
            This leads to the idea of:
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>Absolute Error:</term> the difference between the measured value and the true value (when known).
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, repeated measurements and better instruments improve reliability but never completely remove error.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Three students measure the same desk and obtain <m>120</m> cm, <m>121</m> cm, and <m>119</m> cm. Explain why the measurements are not exactly the same.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                The measurements are not exactly the same because measurement involves estimation. Different students may read the scale slightly differently, estimate between scale markings differently, or start and end the measurement at slightly different points.
            </p>
            <p>
                As a result, small variations in the measurements can occur even when measuring the same object.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>

        <statement>
            <p>
                Why do you think different students are more likely to get similar measurements when using a tape measure than when using a 15 cm ruler?
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Different students are more likely to get similar measurements when using a tape measure because a tape measure can be used to measure the whole length of the desk at once. A <m>15</m> cm ruler has to be moved several times, and small errors can occur each time it is re-positioned. 
            </p>
            <p>
                These small errors may add up, causing different students to obtain slightly different measurements. Therefore, measurements taken with a tape measure are usually more consistent.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

